Data Import and update of Follow-up

Here, we bring in the Dataset and update the Date of Last Follow-up column. THen, we remove SCLC (Small Cell Lung CA) patients since we’re interested in NSCLC outcomes.

The DB lock date was the date this analysis was started: 07/2017. No new patients since 07/2017 are included in this analysis. However, the most updated follow-up data was merged to the dataset as of 12/2017, so we have 6 month follow-up data atleast for all patients.For follow-up, we left_join the database with the most recent follow-up data (FollowUpJoinDb, ManualJoinDB). This is done to make sure that the Death/Last Follow-up and the Vital status fields are the most updated as possible, without NAs.

# data frame of all patients 
PD1_df <<- read.csv("20170630FullDatasetJN-csv.csv", skip=1)

# our follow-up data is incomplete. To complete these data, we first load updated death/last follow-up data from the recently updated version - 12/2017. We left_join to only include the patients that we started with and not add on any new patients. 
FollowUpJoinDb <- read.csv("20180122FollowUpDatesJoinDB-csv.csv", sep=",", header = FALSE)

#-------up date last follow-up date using the more recent XRT database and manual update of select entries 01/2018----------------
PD1_df_merged <<- left_join(PD1_df, FollowUpJoinDb, by=c("MRN"="V1"))
## Warning: Column `MRN`/`V1` joining factors with different levels, coercing
## to character vector
# in the merged datasets, v2 and v3 are from the join db
PD1_df_merged$Index <- c(1:nrow(PD1_df_merged))
PD1_df_merged$Date.of.Death.or.Last.Follow.up <- as.character(PD1_df_merged$Date.of.Death.or.Last.Follow.up)
PD1_df_merged$V3 <- as.character(PD1_df_merged$V3)

UpdateDate <- function (x) {
  if(is.na(PD1_df_merged$Date.of.Death.or.Last.Follow.up[x]) | PD1_df_merged$Date.of.Death.or.Last.Follow.up[x]=="") { 
  PD1_df_merged$Date.of.Death.or.Last.Follow.up[x] <<-  PD1_df_merged$V3[x]
  return(x) 
  }
  # update vital status as well
  if(!is.na(PD1_df_merged$V2[x])) {
    if(!PD1_df_merged$V2[x]==PD1_df_merged$Vital.Status..Alive.1..Dead.0.[x]) PD1_df_merged$Vital.Status..Alive.1..Dead.0.[x]<<- PD1_df_merged$V2[x]
  }
return(x)
}

PD1_df_merged$Index <- lapply(PD1_df_merged$Index, UpdateDate)

# this is the DB with the date merge complete. 
PD1_df <<- PD1_df_merged



# even after this update, there are lots of NAs in the follow-up column, which is critical for survival analysis. For these last 10 or so entries, manual update need. This has been done and saved as a separate csv file which we will bring in similarly join on to PD1_df
ManualJoinDB <- read.csv("StatusUpdate012018.csv", sep =",", header=TRUE)

FindMissingDates <- function (x) {

    if(is.na(PD1_df$Date.of.Death.or.Last.Follow.up[x])) {
      mrnum <<- PD1_df$MRN[x] 
      PD1_df$Date.of.Death.or.Last.Follow.up[x]<<- as.character(ManualJoinDB[ManualJoinDB$MRN==mrnum,2])
      return(x)
    }
    else return(x)
  }

PD1_df$Index <- lapply(PD1_df$Index, FindMissingDates)
# some patients have gone from alive to dead. these are marked as deceased in the status.change column
ManualJoinDB$Index <- c(1:nrow(ManualJoinDB))

SomePeopleDied <- function (x) {
  if(ManualJoinDB$Status.Change[x]=="Deceased") {
    PD1_df[PD1_df$MRN==ManualJoinDB$MRN[x],11]<<-"Deceased"
  return(x)
  }
  return(x)
}
ManualJoinDB$Index <- lapply(ManualJoinDB$Index, SomePeopleDied)

# Need to calculate age from DOB
# add age as a column
age_calc <- function(dob, enddate=Sys.Date(), units='months'){
  if (!inherits(dob, "Date") | !inherits(enddate, "Date"))
    stop("Both dob and enddate must be Date class objects")
  start <- as.POSIXlt(dob)
  end <- as.POSIXlt(enddate)

  years <- end$year - start$year
  if(units=='years'){
    result <- ifelse((end$mon < start$mon) | 
                      ((end$mon == start$mon) & (end$mday < start$mday)),
                      years - 1, years)    
  }else if(units=='months'){
    months <- (years-1) * 12
    result <- months + start$mon
  }else if(units=='days'){
    result <- difftime(end, start, units='days')
  }else{
    stop("Unrecognized units. Please choose years, months, or days.")
  }
  return(result)
}

PD1_df$age <- age_calc(as.Date(PD1_df$DOB, "%m/%d/%Y"), units = "years")

# a proportion test to see if the proportion of patients on combo therapy differs between PD1 pneumonitis+ and PD1 pneumonitis- group

For the patients without pneumonitis, 12 recieved Ipi and 3 recieved Tremelumimab, for a total of 15. So the proportion of patients recieving combo therapy are 11/31 (for the pneumonitis+ group) and 15/158 for the pneumonitis - group

Time to Onset Analysis

This is to reproduce time to onset as described previously (Naidoo et al JCO) for other PD-1 pneumonitis datasets

#-----------------------------------------------------------------

# Time to onset analysis - written 12/13/2017

# we create date to onset by subtracting therapy initiation date from pneumonitis onset date
PneumonitisPts$DaystoOnset <- as.Date(PneumonitisPts$Pneumonitis.Start.Date, format="%m/%d/%Y")-as.Date(PneumonitisPts$First.IO.Treatment.Start.Date.PD.1.PD.L1...manual.update, format="%m/%d/%Y")

# create a concatenated list to plot all patients followed by patients by grade
OnsetByGrade <- cbind(PneumonitisPts$Highest.Pneumonitis.Grade, PneumonitisPts$DaystoOnset)
OnsetTotal <- cbind(PneumonitisPts$Any.Grade.Pneumonitis..Y.1..N.0., PneumonitisPts$DaystoOnset)
OnsetTotal <- rbind(OnsetTotal, OnsetByGrade)
OnsetTotal <- as.data.frame(OnsetTotal)

# get rid of the unknown column (i.e grade ="6")
OnsetTotal <- OnsetTotal[OnsetTotal$V1 < 6,]

# in OnsetTotal, V1 = Grade (1 = all), V2 = days

#calculate mean and median time to onset by grade as well as SD and SEM
MeanTimeToOnset <- aggregate(OnsetTotal$V2, by=list(V1=OnsetTotal$V1), FUN=mean)
MedianTimeToOnset <- aggregate(OnsetTotal$V2, by=list(V1=OnsetTotal$V1), FUN=median)
IQRTimeToOnset <- as.matrix(aggregate(OnsetTotal$V2, by=list(V1=OnsetTotal$V1), FUN=quantile))
NumPerGrade <- aggregate(OnsetTotal$V2, by=list(V1=OnsetTotal$V1), FUN=length)
IQRLower <- as.data.frame(IQRTimeToOnset[,3])
colnames(IQRLower) <- c("x")
IQRHigher <- as.data.frame(IQRTimeToOnset[,5])
colnames(IQRHigher) <- c("x")
 
# plot time to onset. Grade "1" = all grades
plotOnset <- function() {
plot(OnsetTotal$V1, OnsetTotal$V2, ylab="Days to Onset", xlab="Pneumonitis Grade", xaxt="n", col=OnsetTotal$V1*10, pch=1, cex=1.5, xlim=c(0,6))

axis(1, at=1:6)
# add medians
points(MedianTimeToOnset, pch=15,bg="red")
# add error bars
arrows(as.integer(MedianTimeToOnset$V1),  MedianTimeToOnset$x- IQRLower$x, as.integer(MedianTimeToOnset$V1), MedianTimeToOnset$x+IQRHigher$x, lwd = 2, angle = 90,code = 3, length = 0.05)
text(MedianTimeToOnset, labels=MedianTimeToOnset$x, pos=4, offset=0.5, cex=1)
}

Pneumonitis Incidence by Year

Use of Anti-PD1/PD-L1 therapies is not uniform across the 5 years that this data was collected. This analysis looks at incidence by year

#---------pneumonitis incidence by year: coded 12/14/17--------------------
# pull out just the year for pneumonitis start date and grade of pneumonitis from the PneumonitisPts

library(data.table)
library(lubridate)
##

PneumonitisByYear <- as.data.frame(cbind(as.character(PneumonitisPts$Pneumonitis.Start.Date), PneumonitisPts$Highest.Pneumonitis.Grade))
colnames(PneumonitisByYear) <- c("Year", "Grade")

# inner join All patients and pneumonitis patients to create a stacked bar plot

# now, there are more years in the total dataset than in the pneumonitis dataset, so we can't do a inner_join. We'll have to do a one sided left_join, the years where no pneumonitis incidence data is available will be NAs
CombinedIncidenceByYear <- left_join(AllIncidenceByYear, PneumonitisIncidenceByYear,by="Year")

Modeling: Cox PH and Logistic Regression Models

Now the meat of the matter. We want to look at survival differences between patients with and without pneumonitis using univariate (Kaplan-Meier) and multivariate (COx PH Regression) methods. For this, though, we need to first clean up our data significantly. We are doing 2 COX PH models: one for development of pneumonitis (outcome: pneumonitis) and one for survival (outcome: death). The problem with looking at the relationship between pneumonitis and death is that Cox PH mandates that the covariates must be defined at the onset and doing a Kaplan Meier based on pneumonitis disobeyes this rule. So, we will use landmark analysis.

1. Data cleanup for Cox PH REgression analysis

   LR_df$PneumonitisOnset[x] <<- (as.Date(LR_df$Date.of.Death.or.Last.Follow.up[x], format="%m/%d/%Y")-as.Date(LR_df$First.IO.Treatment.Start.Date.PD.1.PD.L1...manual.update[x], format="%m/%d/%Y"))
   return(x)
  }
  return(x)
  
  
}

5. Dealing with Pneumonitis as a time-variable covariate:w

Pneumonitis state is not known at time 0. We will look at this with 2 approaches:

  1. Landmarking. We will landmark at 1, 2,3,6 and 12 months and look at KM curves at these time points

  2. Multi-State Model (death-illness model)

5a. Landmarking

5b. Construction of Multi-State Model

# Second method: Multi-state modeling

# For this we need additional data on Improved Pts

ImprovedPts <- read.table("../ImprovedPtsData/ImprovedPtList2.txt", sep = "\t", header=TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)


# For this, we need the data in the following forms: 
# Form 1: time, patient id (index), tstart, tstop, from_state, to_state, status between tstart and tstop
# Form 2: time, patient id (index), tstart, tstop, state, status
# If Pneumonitis==0, they never developed pneumonitis. So, then, if the patient is Alive, they get one entry, where time=tstart=0, tstop=time_to_death, to_state and from_state are both 1, status = 0 (Alive)

# If Pneumonitis==0 and they died, they get one entry for the transition point from alive to dead.

# if Pneumonitis==1 and they are alive, one entry from No Pneumonitis to Pneumonitis at OnsetTime
# If pneumonits ==1 and they are dead, 2 entries - one to pneumonitis, and annother to death

CoxPHModel_MSM <- CoxPHModel_df
PD1_MSM_df <- PD1_df
# Left Join the CoxPHModelMSM with ImprovedPts
PD1_MSM_df <- left_join(PD1_MSM_df, ImprovedPts, by="MRN")
PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement <- mapply(function (x,y) if(!is.na(y)) return (as.Date(y, format="%m/%d/%Y")-as.Date(x, format="%m/%d/%Y")) else return(0), x=PD1_MSM_df$Pneumonitis.Start.Date, y=PD1_MSM_df$Date.Improved)
PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset <- as.Date(PD1_MSM_df$Pneumonitis.Start.Date, format="%m/%d/%Y")-as.Date(PD1_MSM_df$First.IO.Treatment.Start.Date.PD.1.PD.L1...manual.update, format="%m/%d/%Y")
PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime <- as.Date(PD1_MSM_df$Date.of.Death.or.Last.Follow.up, format="%m/%d/%Y")-as.Date(PD1_MSM_df$First.IO.Treatment.Start.Date.PD.1.PD.L1...manual.update, format="%m/%d/%Y")
PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement <- as.numeric(PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement)
PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset <- as.numeric(PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset)
PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime <- as.numeric(PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime)

PD1_MSM_df$Any.Grade.Pneumonitis..Y.1..N.0. <- lapply(PD1_MSM_df$Any.Grade.Pneumonitis..Y.1..N.0., function (x) if(is.na(x)) return(0) else return (x))
PrepMSMdf <<- function (x) {

  if(PD1_MSM_df$Any.Grade.Pneumonitis..Y.1..N.0.[x]==0)  {
    if(PD1_MSM_df$Vital.Status..Alive.1..Dead.0.[x]=="Alive") {
      # patient has no pneumonitis, is alive. This is state 1
      # form 1  
     if(!exists("Msmdf")) Msmdf <<- c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],1,1,0) 
     else Msmdf <<- rbind(Msmdf, c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],1,1,0) ) 
     # form 2 
     if(!exists("Msmdf2")) {
       Msmdf2 <<- c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],1,0) 
       Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x,PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],1,0) ) 
       }
     else {
       Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],1,0) ) 
  Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x,PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],1,0) ) 
 
     }
    }
    
    if(PD1_MSM_df$Vital.Status..Alive.1..Dead.0.[x]=="Deceased") {
     # This patient did not have pneumonitis, but died. Transition from state 1 to state 3 (death) 
      
      # form 1
      if(!exists("Msmdf")) Msmdf <<- c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],1,3,1) 
     else Msmdf <<- rbind(Msmdf, c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],1,3,1) ) 

      # form 2  
      if(!exists("Msmdf2")) {
        Msmdf2 <<- c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],1,0) 
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],3,1))
      }
     else {
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],1,0)) 
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x,PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],3,1))
     } 
    } 
     
  }
  
  if(PD1_MSM_df$Any.Grade.Pneumonitis..Y.1..N.0.[x]==1) {
    
   if(PD1_MSM_df$Vital.Status..Alive.1..Dead.0.[x]=="Alive") {
     # this patient had pneumonitis, but is alive, so only two transition (1->2 and if improved 2->1)
    # form 1 
     if(!exists("Msmdf")) Msmdf <<- c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],1,2,0) 
     else Msmdf <<- rbind(Msmdf, c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],1,2,0) ) 
   
    # form 2
      
     
    if(PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x]!=0) {
      # add reverse  back to 1 from state 2
     # form 1
    if(!exists("Msmdf")) Msmdf <<- c(x,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x],2,1,0) 
     else Msmdf <<- rbind(Msmdf, c(x,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x],2,1,0)) 
   
    # form 2
       if(!exists("Msmdf2")) {
        Msmdf2 <<- c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaysToOnset[x],1,0) 
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x], PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x], 2,0))
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 1,0))
       Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 1,0))
       } 
        
      else {
         Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],1,0) )
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x], PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x], 2,0))
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 1,0))
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 1,0))
        
        }
     } 
     else {
       if(!exists("Msmdf2")) {
        Msmdf2 <<- c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaysToOnset[x],1,0) 
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 2,0))
       Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 2,0))
 
        }
     else {
         Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],1,0)) 
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 2,0))
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 2,0))
  
        } 
        }
      
     } 
   
     if(PD1_MSM_df$Vital.Status..Alive.1..Dead.0.[x]== "Deceased") {

      if(PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x]==0) {
    # this patient had pneumonitis, but is dead, and did not improve so 2 transitions (1->2, 2->3) 
    # form 1 
      if(!exists("Msmdf")) Msmdf <<- c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],1,2,0) 
     else Msmdf <<- rbind(Msmdf, c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],1,2,0) ) 

      if(!exists("Msmdf")) Msmdf <<- c(x,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],2,3,1) 
     else Msmdf <<- rbind(Msmdf, c(x,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],2,3,1))  
     
    # form 2 
        if(!exists("Msmdf2")) {
        # if pt has pneumonitis on day 0, skip 1st state 
        Msmdf2 <<- c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],1,0) 
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 2,0))
         Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 3,1))
        
          }
     else {
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],1,0))
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 2,0))
         Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 3,1))
           
          }
      
      }
      else {
        # patient had pneumonitis, is dead, but improved before dying. so 1->2, 2->1, 1->3
         if(!exists("Msmdf2")) {
         Msmdf2 <<- c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],1,0) 
        Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x], PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x], 2,0))
         Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 1,0))
         Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 3,1))
        
          }
     else {
         Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x,0,PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x],1,0))
         Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaystoOnset[x], PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x], 2,0))
         Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$DaysToImprovement[x], PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 1,0))
         Msmdf2 <<- rbind(Msmdf2, c(x, PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x],PD1_MSM_df$TotalFollowTime[x], 3,1))
           
          }
      } 
    
    
     }
  }
return(x)  
}

PD1_MSM_df$Index <- lapply(PD1_MSM_df$Index, PrepMSMdf)

  as.numeric(as.matrix(pmatrix.msm(PD_MSM, t=time))[x][y])
}

# develop pmatrix outputs with CIs. For this version of MrNoodle, x is the type of output (TP, lower bound CI, upper bound CI), and y is the state desired. y=1 is 1->1, y=2 is 2->1, y=3 is 3->1, y=4 is 1->2, etc.

# We'll make a second MSM, with no deathexact argument, since not needed
PD_MSM2 <<- msm(state ~ tstart, subject=id, data=Msmdf3, qmatrix=Qm, gen.inits=TRUE,exacttimes=TRUE)

MrNoodleWithCI <- function(time,x,y) {
  as.numeric(as.matrix(pmatrix.msm(PD_MSM2, t=time, ci=c("normal")))[[x]][y])
}

# return the whole thing, no just [[x]][y]. Also we use ci bootstrap which gives more accurate CIs
MrNoodleWithCI2 <- function(time) {
  return(as.matrix(pmatrix.msm(PD_MSM2, t=time, ci=c("normal")))) 
         }

# Zoomedlasagna's Master TP has the following list structure
# List 
#   List #1: TPs
#   List #2: Lower CI
#   List #3: Upper CI

# So, [[1]][[1]] gets to the TP list, then [[1]][[1]][4] gets to the 4th element on that list (see above, corresponds to 1->2)
ZoomedLasagnaWithCI <- data.frame(c(1:1000))
colnames(ZoomedLasagnaWithCI) <- c("times")
ZoomedLasagnaWithCI$MasterTP <- lapply(ZoomedLasagnaWithCI$times, MrNoodleWithCI2)

# let's do the same for all CA patients (The entire PD1_df data frame)
ChemoPtsByYear <- as.data.frame(year(as.Date(as.character(PD1_df$First.IO.Treatment.Start.Date.PD.1.PD.L1...manual.update), format="%m/%d/%Y")))
colnames(AllPtsByYear) <- c("Year")
AllIncidenceByYear <- aggregate(AllPtsByYear$Year, by=list(Year=AllPtsByYear$Year), FUN=length)


# inner join All patients and pneumonitis patients to create a stacked bar plot
# note for the inner join here, i renamed the year column as 'Year' for both Dfs. You don't have to do that, by = c(name1, name2) will match name1 in df_1 to name2 in df_2

# now, there are more years in the total dataset than in the pneumonitis dataset, so we can't do a inner_join. We'll have to do a one sided left_join, the years where no pneumonitis incidence data is available will be NAs
CombinedIncidenceByYear <- left_join(AllIncidenceByYear, PneumonitisIncidenceByYear,by="Year")

# some gymnastics to get this into stacked bar plotform
CombinedIncidenceByYear <- as.data.frame(transpose(CombinedIncidenceByYear))
colnames(CombinedIncidenceByYear) = CombinedIncidenceByYear[1,]
CombinedIncidenceByYear=CombinedIncidenceByYear[-1,]
barplot(as.matrix(CombinedIncidenceByYear), xlab="Year", ylab="Number of cases", legend.text=c("No CIP", "CIP"), args.legend=list(x="topleft"))
